Git Handbook for Senior SRE

Git is a distributed version control system used to track changes in files, coordinate work between engineers, and manage infrastructure/configuration code in production.

This guide covers everything from basic Git to advanced SRE workflows.

1. What is Git

Git is an open-source distributed version control system.

Key features:

Tracks changes in files

Maintains history of code

Enables collaboration

Supports branching and merging

Works locally and remotely

Core concepts:

Repository: project tracked by Git

Commit: snapshot of project state

Branch: parallel line of development

Remote: hosted repository (GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket)

2. Installing Git

Check if Git is installed:

git --version

Install Git:

Ubuntu/Debian:

sudo apt install git

RHEL/CentOS:

sudo yum install git -y

Verify installation:

git --version
3. Initial Git Configuration

Set your identity:

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your@email.com"

View configuration:

git config --list
4. Creating a Repository
mkdir git-lab
cd git-lab
git init
ls -a  # shows .git directory
5. Git Architecture & Workflow

Git uses three main areas:

Working Directory: where you edit files

Staging Area (Index): files prepared for commit

Local Repository: commits stored permanently

Workflow Example:

edit file → git add → git commit
6. File States
State	Description
Untracked	New file not yet tracked
Modified	Tracked file changed
Staged	Ready to commit
Committed	Snapshot saved in repository

Check status:

git status
7. First Commit (Lab)
touch app.txt
echo "Hello SRE" >> app.txt
git add app.txt
git commit -m "initial commit"
git log
8. Adding Files
git add file.txt       # stage a specific file
git add .              # stage all files
git status             # check staged files
9. Viewing Commit History
git log                  # full commit history
git log --oneline        # short version
git log --graph --oneline --all   # graph view
git show <commit_id>     # detailed info
10. Git Diff
git diff                 # changes in working directory
git diff --staged        # staged changes
git diff <commit1> <commit2>   # compare commits
11. Undoing Changes
git restore file.txt                  # discard changes in working directory
git restore --staged file.txt        # unstage changes
git revert <commit_id>               # safely undo a commit
git reset --hard <commit_id>         # reset to previous commit (dangerous)
12. Branching
git branch                      # list branches
git branch feature-login        # create branch
git checkout -b feature-login   # create & switch
git switch -c feature-login     # alternative to checkout
git checkout main               # switch branch
git branch -d feature-login     # delete branch safely
git branch -D feature-login     # force delete
git branch -m new-name          # rename branch
13. Merging Branches
git checkout main
git merge feature-login

Merge Types:

Fast-forward merge

Merge commit (no fast-forward)

14. Merge Conflicts

When conflicts occur:

<<<<<<< HEAD
code from current branch
=======
code from feature branch
>>>>>>> feature-login

Resolve Steps:

Edit conflicted files

Stage changes: git add file

Commit: git commit

15. Remote Repositories

Common platforms: GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket

git clone <repo_url>            # copy remote repo
git remote add origin <url>     # add remote
git remote -v                   # view remotes
git remote remove origin        # remove remote
16. Push & Pull
git push origin main            # push branch
git push -u origin main         # set upstream
git push --all origin           # push all branches
git pull origin main            # pull changes
git fetch                       # download changes without merging
git push --tags                 # push tags
17. Stashing

Temporarily save uncommitted changes:

git stash                  # save
git stash list             # list stashes
git stash show <stash_id>  # view stash changes
git stash apply <stash_id> # apply stash
git stash pop              # apply and remove stash
git stash drop <stash_id>  # delete stash
git stash clear            # delete all stashes
18. Tags
git tag -a v1.0 -m "first release"
git tag
git show v1.0
git push --tags
19. Advanced Git (Senior SRE Focus)
Git Rebase
git rebase main

Linear history, cleaner logs

Git Cherry-Pick
git cherry-pick <commit_id>

Apply a specific commit, useful for hotfixes

Git Reflog (Recovery)
git reflog
git reset --hard HEAD@{2}   # recover lost commit
Git Bisect (Debugging)
git bisect start
git bisect bad
git bisect good <commit>

Binary search to find faulty commit

20. Git Hooks

.git/hooks/ directory

Examples: pre-commit, pre-push, post-merge

Use cases: tests, security checks, formatting enforcement

21. Git Submodules
git submodule add <repo_url>
git submodule init
git submodule update

Manage nested repositories

22. Git Troubleshooting (SRE Section)

Recover deleted commit:

git reflog
git reset --hard <commit>

Undo bad merge:

git reset --hard HEAD~1

Restore deleted file:

git checkout <commit> -- file.txt

Find bug introduction commit:

git bisect
23. Git Best Practices for SRE

Branches: feature/*, bugfix/*, hotfix/*

Commit messages:

fix: memory leak
feat: retry logic
docs: update README

Avoid force pushes on shared branches

Use pull requests for review

Small, logical commits

24. Production Workflow Example
git checkout -b fix-memory-leak
git add .
git commit -m "fix: memory leak in worker"
git push origin fix-memory-leak

Workflow:

Create branch → Implement → Commit → Push → PR → Review → Merge → Deploy

